I asked the owner of formulas to see if he could change the license: This is his response (https://github.com/vinci1it2000/formulas/issues/33):

Unfortunately, I cannot change the license. But you have two options:

The Apache license is one of the upstream compatible licenses of the EUPL. Hence, the "derivative work" has to be redistributed under the EUPL.

If you don't want to use the EUPL, you can use the functionality of formulas as it is (i.e., without merging the source code), following the example of chapter 5.6 of the EUPL guidelines. Therefore, if you need extra functionalities, you can propose those through pull requests with the changes and/or the features that you want to integrate into formulas.
I don't see why we should block on this, since we're not merging the formulas library into superset, we're just using the library. Am I reading this wrong ?

@etr2460 

> Is there a reason why you choose to create individual API functions instead of a set of redux actions to fetch and update tags? It makes sense to pull the tagging actions into its own file because it would be shared between both Explore and Dashboard views, but I think that maintaining the state of tags in its own redux store would be more typical and follow the patterns i've seen throughout superset already.

Great question. Yeah, we've been running this code at Lyft for maybe a year now, so it's definitely outdated and would be written differently from scratch today.

IIRC we went with API functions since the state lives outside the applications (explore, dashboards, SQL Lab). Maybe @mistercrunch remembers better?

> I would recommend creating a new directory in assets/src/tags to keep the component files, the main tags page, the redux actions and the reducers and then wire up the required state to both explore and dashboard components. It would make tagging consistent with the rest of the app, clearer, and easier to maintain.

For instance, if I don't correctly `from pydruid.utils.having import Having`, then I can't declare DimSelector. If I don't declare DimSelector, then I can't use `_get_having_obj(self, col, op, eq)` in models.py. I believe the observed bug has its origins in changes introduced by #7453, which changes table names from strings to dicts/objects:
- Before: tables were strings of format `'my_table'` or `'my_schema.my_table'`
- Now: `{ schema: 'my_schema', table: 'my_table' }`

The change was done because many engines support periods in the object names, which confused the frontend. However, apparently there were side-effects that were not covered by unit tests. If having tables in object format causes problems, one solution could be to make them strings again, but make sure periods in object names are properly escaped.
